<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-08-27T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-08-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="447" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d447">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">881.113/33: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Diplomatic Agent and Consul General at
                                    Tangier</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Blake</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tangier</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-08-27T17:00:00+00:00">August 27, 1936—5
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received August 28—10:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>22. Department’s telegraphic instruction No. 11, August 24, 2
                                    p.m.<note n="62" xml:id="d447fn62">See footnote 57, <ref target="#pg_500">p. 500</ref>.</note> Difficulties
                                foreshadowed in my telegram No. 21, August 23, 1 p.m., are arising
                                in acute form. Greatest caution advisable. Am consequently taking no
                                action in matter of acceptance of oil dahir pending developments.
                                Have under consideration and will shortly submit for Department’s
                                approval formula under which dahir may be accepted without any
                                breach of neutrality on our part.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Blake</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>